    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at our warehouse reports and noticed our shrinkage numbers have jumped a lot this quarter. how do i factor this into our inventory turnover ratio so i can show the impact to my manager?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To factor in shrinkage, you should adjust the \"Cost of Goods Sold\" (COGS) figure in your inventory calculation. Instead of using the book COGS, use the actual cost of goods sold *plus* the monetary value of the lost inventory due to shrinkage. This adjusted, higher cost will cause the numerator of the inventory turnover ratio to increase, which in turn will lower the resulting ratio. This lower ratio accurately reflects the increased inefficiency caused by shrinkage.",
      "source": "target",
