    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so basically the more we lose we look less efficient. i'm also trying to figure out if this is a systemic issue or just random error. do you have any advice on how to differentiate between actual theft and just bad record keeping when looking at these numbers?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Differentiating theft from poor record-keeping requires a multi-faceted approach beyond just the turnover ratio. Cross-reference high-shrinkage items with transaction logs and cycle count data to see if discrepancies align with specific shifts or personnel. Analyzing patterns, such as shrinkage occurring only in certain high-value or easily accessible zones, can point strongly toward internal theft. If the shrinkage is spread randomly across all types of goods without pattern, it suggests more generalized record-keeping or process issues.",
      "source": "target",
